Morphology of stained specimens. Infraciliary characteristics and the macronucleus of
E. riograndensis
were easily revealed by protargol staining. Reticulate somatic myonemes extended from the epistomial disk to the scopula of the zooid (
Figure 5
). The trochal band was located 10 to 15 µm, on average adoral of the scopula (
Figure 6
). The oral infraciliature was typical of peritrich ciliates and presented an inner polykinety and an outer haplokinety that made 1 ½ circuits around the peristome before entering the infundibulum. Three infundibular polykinetids (PK 1 , PK 2 , and PK 3 ) all consisting of three rows of kinetosomes, were observed (
Figure 7
): rows of PK 1 were equal in length and ended adstomally at the margin of the cytostome (
Figure 8
). Rows of PK 2 also were equal in length, terminating at the adstomal curvature of PK 1 on one end and merging with the rows of PK 1 abstomally (
Figure 8
and
11
). PK 3 consisted of three long rows of kinetosomes of equal length that terminated approximately midway between the adstomal ends of PK 1 and PK 2 (
Figure 9
and
11
).
